01:53.113 --> 01:55.849
The Basque country
is an autonomous region,

01:55.883 --> 01:58.419
a place, a culture,

01:58.452 --> 02:01.689
where the Basque language
is spoken.

02:01.722 --> 02:05.359
Strictly speaking, it's an area
straddling Spain and France

02:05.393 --> 02:09.197
at the western end
of the Pyrenees.

02:09.229 --> 02:11.098
They've been
speaking Basque here

02:11.131 --> 02:15.836
long before the first
Roman arrived in 65 B.C.

02:15.869 --> 02:18.372
It is a very old language.

02:18.406 --> 02:20.208
How old, like the question of

02:20.241 --> 02:23.211
how far back their history goes
and where it begins,

02:23.244 --> 02:25.045
is not known.

02:25.078 --> 02:27.381
The best answer
anyone can give you

02:27.415 --> 02:32.052
is "long, long ago."

02:36.424 --> 02:38.226
What did this area...
What did this coastline

02:38.259 --> 02:41.795
look like
back in, uh, 17th century?

02:41.829 --> 02:42.830
So different, right?

02:42.863 --> 02:43.964
So different.

02:43.997 --> 02:45.899
There's more landscape now.

02:45.933 --> 02:49.570
The sea went farther
into the land.

02:49.603 --> 02:53.574
Maybe some houses
like three or four there,

02:53.607 --> 02:56.477
but the other one wasn't there.

02:56.510 --> 02:58.679
The church there wasn't there.

02:58.712 --> 03:01.349
There was a small church, maybe.

03:01.382 --> 03:05.686
If that mountain houses
watching to the sea,

03:05.719 --> 03:06.987
was impossible.

03:07.020 --> 03:08.682
All the traditional houses
were pointed inland.

03:08.689 --> 03:09.657
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

03:09.690 --> 03:11.058
Before
the industrial revolution,

03:11.091 --> 03:12.159
with no heating systems,

03:12.192 --> 03:13.520
Right, the wind
would come in and...

03:13.527 --> 03:15.396
You couldn't afford
watching into the sea

03:15.429 --> 03:16.830
because the wind
and the humidity

03:16.864 --> 03:19.032
make it impossible to maintain
that kind of living.

03:19.066 --> 03:22.703
So every house
has windows to the sea,

03:22.736 --> 03:24.238
it means it's not so old.

03:24.272 --> 03:27.375
♪

03:27.408 --> 03:29.677
Edorta Jimenez
and his daughter Arathi

03:29.710 --> 03:32.680
are both acclaimed authors
and proud Basque.

03:32.713 --> 03:37.050
And they know as much about
their history as can be known.

03:37.084 --> 03:40.388
Sea barnacles, or percebes,
are much loved here.

03:40.421 --> 03:42.690
Steamed briefly
with a little salt,

03:42.723 --> 03:45.693
simple,
like much of Basque cooking.

03:50.097 --> 03:51.899
That's delicious.

03:51.932 --> 03:52.900
It's very, very good.

03:52.933 --> 03:55.235
I love these.

03:55.269 --> 03:56.570
And thank you for coming.

03:56.604 --> 03:58.143
How long do you think
the Basque people

03:58.171 --> 03:59.873
lived in this community?

03:59.907 --> 04:01.375
Or does anybody know?

04:01.409 --> 04:03.877
- 25,000 years.
- 25,000 years.

04:03.911 --> 04:05.212
Yeah, we are living here.

04:05.245 --> 04:06.880
So you're talking, like,
Cro-Magnon.

04:06.914 --> 04:08.048
Yes.

04:08.081 --> 04:09.983
- All the way back.
- All the way back.

04:10.017 --> 04:11.218
And the language?

04:11.251 --> 04:12.252
From here?

04:12.286 --> 04:13.487
We really don't know.

04:13.521 --> 04:17.558
It is the only language
in Europe that we know of

04:17.591 --> 04:20.628
that doesn't have anything to do
with the rest of the languages,

04:20.661 --> 04:23.063
that doesn't come from
the same place.

04:23.096 --> 04:25.299
And the Basque genetic signature

04:25.333 --> 04:27.968
is also seemingly unique.

04:28.001 --> 04:32.406
I mean, nobody's finding
any relatives in anywhere.

04:32.440 --> 04:36.076
They did this research with
people's DNA from this area...

04:36.109 --> 04:37.244
Yeah.

04:37.277 --> 04:39.480
And the conclusion was,

04:39.513 --> 04:42.416
it's the same people that was
living here, uh...

04:42.450 --> 04:44.318
25,000 years ago.

04:47.321 --> 04:51.091
♪

04:51.124 --> 04:52.125
So do you believe that:

04:52.159 --> 04:54.428
the Basque
have always been here,

04:54.462 --> 04:57.498
that the language has been
influenced by nobody else?

04:57.531 --> 05:00.368
And the mystery, Anthony,
is that we are in the way.

05:00.401 --> 05:01.369
Yep.

05:01.402 --> 05:03.103
On the Iberian Peninsula,

05:03.136 --> 05:06.106
you have two natural ways,
two natural pass.

05:06.139 --> 05:08.442
One is
in the Mediterranean side,

05:08.476 --> 05:10.944
and the other one
is on the Atlantic side.

05:10.978 --> 05:14.848
And we are in the way
from the north to the south.

05:14.882 --> 05:19.019
Well, good negotiators.

05:19.052 --> 05:20.554
Good fighters, good negotiators.

05:20.588 --> 05:22.490
Yeah, who knows?

05:24.858 --> 05:25.358
♪

05:33.534 --> 05:34.034
