07:38.225 --> 07:41.361
These are what you call
pinchos around here,

07:41.394 --> 07:42.462
not tapas.

07:42.496 --> 07:43.964
These incredible batteries

07:43.997 --> 07:46.166
of delicious, delicious things

07:46.199 --> 07:47.868
generally located
near one another

07:47.901 --> 07:50.704
so you can easily
and very pleasurably go out

07:50.738 --> 07:53.306
for what's called a poteo,
a bar crawl,

07:53.340 --> 07:56.877
grazing through the specialties
of each place.

08:00.013 --> 08:02.783
I would like to start
with a little bit of beer.

08:02.816 --> 08:04.384
What do you think?
Yeah.

08:04.417 --> 08:06.887
Not too much, because we are
going to other place, huh?

08:06.920 --> 08:07.888
Welcome.
Chin chin.

08:07.921 --> 08:09.623
- Thank you. Chin chin.
- Eh? Gabriella?

08:09.657 --> 08:12.125
Gabriella Ranelli
has worked closely

08:12.159 --> 08:13.661
with both Arzaks for years

08:13.694 --> 08:15.729
and is considered
a leading authority

08:15.763 --> 08:18.298
on the Basque culinary scene.

08:18.331 --> 08:19.359
Have to move
from place to place.

08:19.366 --> 08:21.068
'Cause the important thing is,

08:21.101 --> 08:22.335
you have different atmospheres;

08:22.369 --> 08:23.597
you have different
flavor profiles.

08:23.604 --> 08:25.305
People here
really like the classics.

08:25.338 --> 08:26.473
You know, people go after

08:26.506 --> 08:28.008
exactly what
they're looking for.

08:28.041 --> 08:31.511
Fried quail egg,
blood sausage, and peppers.

08:31.545 --> 08:34.313
This is like a whole breakfast
on a piece of bread.

08:34.347 --> 08:35.482
Wait a minute.
What's that?

08:35.515 --> 08:36.610
Uh, sea urchin.
You want to try some?

08:36.616 --> 08:39.086
Sea urchin with onion and cava.

08:39.119 --> 08:41.421
You are good
at eating pinchos, eh?

08:42.590 --> 08:44.592
It's so difficult to stop, no?
Yeah.

08:47.628 --> 08:51.364
♪

08:51.398 --> 08:53.667
Walking anywhere
in San Sebastián

08:53.701 --> 08:55.035
with Juan Mari Arzak

08:55.068 --> 08:57.504
is like walking through Chicago
with Michael Jordan

08:57.537 --> 09:00.674
or Washington, D.C.
with George Washington.

09:00.708 --> 09:01.842
He's the godfather,

09:01.875 --> 09:04.878
universally beloved
and respected.

09:04.912 --> 09:05.879
You're like Elvis.

09:07.047 --> 09:08.355
He's like Elvis Presley, huh?
Si.

09:12.820 --> 09:15.789
♪

09:15.823 --> 09:20.594
Why do the Basque,
unique among their neighbors,

09:20.628 --> 09:22.863
obsessively insist on

09:22.896 --> 09:25.799
such high-quality ingredients
for everything?

09:32.239 --> 09:34.274
People have a passion for food.

09:34.307 --> 09:36.076
- Why here?
- Por qué?

09:36.109 --> 09:37.778
I don't know.

09:37.811 --> 09:38.779
Always been this way.

09:38.812 --> 09:40.047
Until about 80 years ago,

09:40.080 --> 09:41.811
there wasn't a lot of this stuff
written down.

09:50.257 --> 09:52.626
♪

09:52.660 --> 09:53.994
Right in here.
Oh, okay.

09:54.027 --> 09:55.963
Yeah, I figured how...
We're not walking by here.

09:55.996 --> 09:58.231
Ganbara: my favorite place.

09:58.265 --> 10:01.401
I come here every time
like a heat-seeking missile.

10:01.434 --> 10:03.470
This is where you'll find
Juan Mari every Sunday.

10:03.503 --> 10:04.972
This is the first place

10:05.005 --> 10:06.499
anyone ever brought me
in San Sebastián.

10:06.506 --> 10:07.741
- Really?
- Yes.

10:07.775 --> 10:10.844
Ibérico ham with mushrooms
are amazing.

10:10.878 --> 10:13.413
Crab tartlets: extraordinary.

10:13.446 --> 10:14.481
Mmm!

10:14.514 --> 10:15.582
Oh, man.

10:15.615 --> 10:17.417
But this, the house specialty,

10:17.450 --> 10:18.919
what they're most famous for,

10:18.952 --> 10:21.588
is the be-all
and end-all for me.

10:21.621 --> 10:24.124
Seared wild mushrooms
and foie gras

10:24.157 --> 10:27.027
with a raw egg yolk
gently draped over the top

10:27.060 --> 10:30.097
to sizzle and commingle
with the hot fungi.

10:30.130 --> 10:32.599
This plate, what can you do
to make it better?

10:32.632 --> 10:33.860
- No, it's impossible.
- Leave like that.

10:33.867 --> 10:35.628
It's perfect.
There's no improving this dish.

10:35.635 --> 10:36.770
No.

10:36.804 --> 10:39.039
Now nobody talks.
Only we eat.

10:39.072 --> 10:40.265
Right.
It's a code of silence.

10:44.077 --> 10:47.848
♪

10:56.924 --> 11:00.627
♪

11:03.663 --> 11:07.167
♪

11:10.203 --> 11:10.703
♪

11:18.912 --> 11:20.313
We are in the Basque country.

11:20.347 --> 11:21.715
In a place called Pasaia

11:21.749 --> 11:24.985
near San Sebastián.

11:25.018 --> 11:28.588
This was the main Basque port
in the Middle Age.

11:33.193 --> 11:34.494
Come on!

11:34.527 --> 11:36.496
The Basque ships,
in different times,

11:36.529 --> 11:39.032
they were the top
of the maritime technology.

11:39.066 --> 11:40.333
And because of that,

11:40.367 --> 11:43.904
they could face
the big challenge of the ocean.

11:43.937 --> 11:46.206
This is a very old tradition.

11:48.641 --> 11:51.745
See, we have a real language,
we have a very old culture.

11:51.779 --> 11:54.782
And that culture has been always
looking at the sea.

11:54.815 --> 11:55.315
♪

12:01.221 --> 12:03.190
According to my Basque friends,

12:03.223 --> 12:04.858
the Basque discovered America...

12:04.892 --> 12:06.526
and didn't tell anyone.
That's right.

12:06.559 --> 12:07.720
And who would they tell anyway?

12:07.727 --> 12:09.196
Well,
they didn't want to attract

12:09.229 --> 12:11.198
the attention
of other fishermen.

12:11.231 --> 12:12.299
That's the reason.

12:12.332 --> 12:16.036
So you see, the maritime
official history

12:16.069 --> 12:20.573
has been written by kings
that wanted to claim something,

12:20.607 --> 12:22.542
you know, like, "This is mine."

12:22.575 --> 12:25.212
This is mine.
I want everybody to know that."

12:25.245 --> 12:27.480
Fishermen,
they did the opposite thing.

12:27.514 --> 12:29.883
So that's why now
these archaeologists

12:29.917 --> 12:32.986
are finding evidences
of our past,

12:33.020 --> 12:34.554
and that's very important
for us.

12:34.587 --> 12:37.557
Xavier Ogote is a shipwright
and founder

12:37.590 --> 12:40.727
of the Basque
Maritime Heritage Museum,

12:40.760 --> 12:42.896
where he works
to preserve and promote

12:42.930 --> 12:47.400
the proud history of
Basque exploration of the sea.

12:47.434 --> 12:51.071
When I was a kid, I used to
go to San Sebastián port

12:51.104 --> 12:52.906
and start fishing there.

12:52.940 --> 12:55.108
I remember
the fishing boats come in,

12:55.142 --> 12:59.346
in and out every day,
wooden boats, fantastic.

12:59.379 --> 13:01.248
When I grew older,
I witnessed how

13:01.281 --> 13:04.351
all the traditional wooden boats
that I loved so much

13:04.384 --> 13:07.020
were being replaced
by fiberglass boats.

13:07.054 --> 13:11.591
So when I was 18, I decided
to become a boat builder.

13:11.624 --> 13:13.861
So for me,
it was one of the most

13:13.894 --> 13:16.763
enriching experiences
of my life.

13:19.799 --> 13:20.299
♪

13:36.416 --> 13:39.719
We created Albaola,
like, 20 years ago

13:39.752 --> 13:41.721
because nobody knew
about the Basque

13:41.754 --> 13:43.957
and their relationship
with the sea.

13:45.758 --> 13:47.127
And at the moment,
we are building

13:47.160 --> 13:49.229
a dream of my life coming true,

13:49.262 --> 13:54.801
which is a 16th-century
Basque whaling galleon.

13:54.834 --> 13:57.304
My hope is that
through this project,

13:57.337 --> 13:59.172
the Basque people will know more

13:59.206 --> 14:01.741
about our maritime history,

14:01.774 --> 14:05.345
they will be proud
of their ancestors.

14:05.378 --> 14:07.480
We decided to build this ship.

14:07.514 --> 14:09.149
I mean, it's... nobody ask us.

14:09.182 --> 14:12.519
♪

14:12.552 --> 14:15.355
This used to be the center of
the world for boat building.

14:15.388 --> 14:19.159
Bad times for the Spanish navy
was good times for the Basque

14:19.192 --> 14:21.494
because if a lot of ships
are sinking,

14:21.528 --> 14:23.363
that means more work here.

14:23.396 --> 14:26.366
The Basque were
the first whalers...

14:26.399 --> 14:28.035
Industrial whalers...

14:28.068 --> 14:29.869
In a time in which
the Basque were

14:29.903 --> 14:32.572
the only people hunting whales
industrially.

14:32.605 --> 14:33.941
How many guys?

14:33.974 --> 14:36.043
In a classic rowing boat,
there's seven people.

14:36.076 --> 14:37.377
Okay, seven people.

14:37.410 --> 14:39.846
Guy out on front, the strongest
guy with a harpoon.

14:39.879 --> 14:40.847
That's right.

14:40.880 --> 14:42.382
Whole lot of rope.

14:42.415 --> 14:43.683
200 meters rope.

14:43.716 --> 14:44.751
How big is the boat?

14:44.784 --> 14:46.186
8 meters.

14:46.219 --> 14:47.254
8 meters.

14:47.287 --> 14:49.856
If the ropes get too wet,
you sink.

14:49.889 --> 14:51.358
If you fall overboard, you die.

14:51.391 --> 14:52.559
You die.

14:52.592 --> 14:54.054
- If the boat capsizes...
- Everybody dies.

14:54.061 --> 14:55.228
You die.
Right.

14:55.262 --> 14:59.432
You have to pull that whale
to the land,

14:59.466 --> 15:00.433
rowing.

15:00.467 --> 15:01.868
A 60-ton whale.

15:01.901 --> 15:03.636
- 60 tons.
- 60 tons.

15:03.670 --> 15:06.239
Metric.
You know, that's, like, big.

15:06.273 --> 15:07.975
So what happens
if everything goes well?

15:08.008 --> 15:09.476
Well, you become very rich.

15:11.178 --> 15:12.612
♪

15:12.645 --> 15:15.382
This place is the famous Elkano

15:15.415 --> 15:17.884
in the seaside village
of Getaria,

15:17.917 --> 15:20.887
a place known and loved
by chefs all over the world

15:20.920 --> 15:23.723
for what they call
their Paleolithic cooking,

15:23.756 --> 15:26.059
the straight-up
application of fire

15:26.093 --> 15:30.998
and a very few ingredients
to make, well, magic of a kind.

15:31.031 --> 15:34.767
♪

15:34.801 --> 15:38.005
Rock prawn, the head and body
are cooked separately.

15:38.038 --> 15:42.075
The body is served nearly raw,
what they call semi-ceviche,

15:42.109 --> 15:43.810
while the heads are grilled.

15:43.843 --> 15:45.245
Oh!

15:45.278 --> 15:46.980
That's nice.
This is gonna be good.

15:47.014 --> 15:48.281
That was very nice.

15:48.315 --> 15:50.583
Squid served the Pelayo way,

15:50.617 --> 15:54.754
grilled with an onion
green pepper sauce.

15:54.787 --> 15:56.089
Wow, look at this.

15:56.123 --> 15:57.290
Excellent.
Ah.

15:57.324 --> 15:59.159
Look at that.
He puts the tentacles...

15:59.192 --> 16:00.427
- Oh, yeah.
- Inside. Nice.

16:00.460 --> 16:03.830
♪

16:03.863 --> 16:05.265
And kokotxas...

16:05.298 --> 16:07.167
About as bone-deep, old-school,

16:07.200 --> 16:09.102
fundamentally Basque
an ingredient

16:09.136 --> 16:11.271
or a passion as there is...

16:11.304 --> 16:13.673
The jowls or chins of hake,

16:13.706 --> 16:16.209
cooked pil pil style
in olive oil

16:16.243 --> 16:18.678
and swirled constantly
to emulsify the oil

16:18.711 --> 16:20.613
with the fish's natural gelatin.

16:20.647 --> 16:23.616
What we like is
the quality of the product.

16:23.650 --> 16:27.154
We like to have everything
alive in our mouth.

16:27.187 --> 16:28.155
Oh, these are the...

16:28.188 --> 16:29.522
Yeah.

16:29.556 --> 16:31.458
- Beautiful.
- But this is good food.

16:31.491 --> 16:32.625
- Look at that.
- Yeah.

16:32.659 --> 16:34.694
So this is a good time
to talk about cod.

16:34.727 --> 16:37.130
Because the Basque are not
getting to America

16:37.164 --> 16:39.532
or Newfoundland
without salt fish, right?

16:39.566 --> 16:42.969
If you didn't have
protein that lasted,

16:43.002 --> 16:45.138
you could not project,
you could not explore,

16:45.172 --> 16:46.699
and you could not
project military power.

16:46.706 --> 16:47.807
Absolutely.

16:47.840 --> 16:49.876
In the early times,
something we know

16:49.909 --> 16:52.645
is that the Basque were
the only ones drying the cod.

16:52.679 --> 16:54.814
Sea salt, we lack of it.

16:54.847 --> 16:56.549
And so we were forced to dry it.

16:56.583 --> 17:01.988
And dry... dry cod, you could
preserve it for years.

17:05.023 --> 17:05.523
♪

17:09.862 --> 17:12.765
But it's this dish that brings
passionate eaters to Elkano

17:12.799 --> 17:14.701
from all across the world:

17:14.733 --> 17:16.336
the turbot, grilled...

17:16.368 --> 17:17.337
Look at that.

17:17.369 --> 17:18.838
That is beautiful.
Yeah.

17:18.871 --> 17:20.272
Perfectly over coals,

17:20.307 --> 17:24.176
and then portioned out expertly
by owner Aitor Arregui

17:24.211 --> 17:26.846
so as to highlight
each and every unique bit

17:26.878 --> 17:28.848
and its special characteristics.

17:28.881 --> 17:31.017
- All the white points?
- Yeah.

17:31.050 --> 17:32.519
This is the protein of the fish.

17:32.552 --> 17:33.786
And it is good to eat.

17:33.820 --> 17:35.688
We can make it like emulsion.

17:35.722 --> 17:37.890
The light gelatinous skin...

17:37.924 --> 17:39.192
Beautiful.

17:39.226 --> 17:41.528
Its soft and slightly
caramelized flesh.

17:41.561 --> 17:42.895
Mmm.

17:42.929 --> 17:43.896
Wow.

17:43.930 --> 17:47.200
The fat, unctuous belly.

17:47.234 --> 17:49.636
He's finding every single
secret of the fish.

17:49.669 --> 17:50.870
Mm-hmm.

17:50.903 --> 17:53.606
The bones, tiny scraps
of the sweetest meat

17:53.640 --> 17:54.607
clinging to them.

17:54.641 --> 17:55.875
Thank you.

17:57.244 --> 17:58.211
Mmm.

17:58.245 --> 17:59.979
One dish, a mosaic

18:00.012 --> 18:02.982
of many distinct flavors
and textures,

18:03.015 --> 18:05.318
all them epically delicious.

18:05.352 --> 18:07.320
♪

18:07.354 --> 18:09.156
It was like an anatomy lesson.

18:09.189 --> 18:10.490
Yeah, absolutely.

18:13.526 --> 18:14.026
♪

18:30.210 --> 18:31.178
♪

18:44.056 --> 18:44.556
♪

19:32.405 --> 19:36.343
♪

19:36.376 --> 19:38.311
How old is the restaurant?

19:38.345 --> 19:40.012
It is 1897.

19:40.046 --> 19:41.648
1897.

19:41.681 --> 19:44.817
Starting with great-grand...
Great-grandparents?

19:44.851 --> 19:46.653
I feel at home at this table.

19:46.686 --> 19:50.022
It is not my first time here
by a long shot.

19:50.056 --> 19:51.691
I am among friends,

19:51.724 --> 19:54.994
friends who feel now
like family.

20:49.449 --> 20:51.551
So how many years
in the restaurant business?

21:07.600 --> 21:10.403
In 1976, 12 Basque chefs

21:10.437 --> 21:12.405
under the influence
of the recently emerged

21:12.439 --> 21:14.807
nouvelle cuisine movement
in France,

21:14.841 --> 21:18.077
formed what later became known
as the gang of 12,

21:18.110 --> 21:20.146
committing themselves
to both modernizing

21:20.179 --> 21:22.148
and protecting
the culinary traditions

21:22.181 --> 21:23.783
of their culture.

21:23.816 --> 21:27.119
Juan Mari Arzak was at
the forefront of that effort.

21:27.153 --> 21:29.789
His daughter Elena
continues to honor

21:29.822 --> 21:32.992
both that commitment
and that responsibility.

21:33.025 --> 21:34.193
♪

21:34.226 --> 21:37.096
The food is innovative,
wildly creative,

21:37.129 --> 21:41.133
forward thinking,
but always, always Basque.

21:41.167 --> 21:44.170
Marinated prawns
on lemongrass and mint

21:44.203 --> 21:47.440
with beetroot and crunchy krill.

21:47.474 --> 21:49.876
For us,
it's the essence of the sea.

21:49.909 --> 21:51.611
Mmm!
Oh, man.

21:51.644 --> 21:54.847
Roast pigeon with mastic
and potato.

21:54.881 --> 21:57.617
And this pigeon
is really very tender.

21:57.650 --> 21:59.452
You will see.
I love it.

22:12.865 --> 22:16.202
Grilled hake jowls with
teff seeds and fresh almonds

22:16.235 --> 22:18.304
served in a bamboo leaf.

22:25.512 --> 22:28.047
Grilled monkfish
with a pecan paste

22:28.080 --> 22:31.384
and hieroglyphics
of pumpkin and sweet pea.

22:31.418 --> 22:32.485
Was it always like this?

22:32.519 --> 22:34.654
I mean, his mother,
his grandmother.

22:34.687 --> 22:37.524
Was it always a menu
that changed every day?

22:37.557 --> 22:40.026
What did you have to have
on the menu?

22:59.045 --> 23:03.450
White tuna with green melon
and a jackfruit sauce.

23:16.062 --> 23:17.430
♪

23:18.898 --> 23:20.867
♪

23:32.411 --> 23:35.214
Squid with walnut ginger paste,

23:35.247 --> 23:39.886
psyllium sauce,
and black tomato.

23:39.919 --> 23:41.496
Is he ever gonna take off
the chef jacket?

23:41.521 --> 23:42.489
What is his plan?

23:45.758 --> 23:46.726
Ah!

23:46.759 --> 23:48.094
I knew he was gonna say this.

23:49.929 --> 23:51.698
I would like to die
at this table.

23:55.101 --> 23:56.068
I like.

23:56.102 --> 23:57.403
Not tonight.

23:57.436 --> 23:58.404
Not tonight.

23:58.437 --> 23:59.672
- Pronto, no.
- No.

23:59.706 --> 24:00.640
Bueno.

24:09.015 --> 24:09.515
♪

24:14.887 --> 24:18.858
I first came here in,
I think, 2001.

24:18.891 --> 24:20.326
15 years ago.

24:22.361 --> 24:23.930
You know, my father
died very young.

24:23.963 --> 24:26.032
But, look,
I'd like him to know that

24:26.065 --> 24:28.367
since the first time
I came here, he's...

24:28.400 --> 24:31.470
I feel like he's looked after me
like a father.

24:31.504 --> 24:34.774
He's been a loyal
and good friend and supporter,

24:34.807 --> 24:37.109
and I want him to know
I appreciate it.

24:47.153 --> 24:48.923
I mean, he's only 14 years
older than me, but

24:50.923 --> 24:51.891
Not too much, eh?

24:51.924 --> 24:52.892
No.

24:52.925 --> 24:54.060
Could be my older brother.

24:56.596 --> 24:59.131
Yes, yes, yes.

24:59.165 --> 25:00.132
It better.

25:00.166 --> 25:02.068
I am the big brother.

25:02.101 --> 25:04.036
Yes, big brother.

25:04.070 --> 25:05.805
No, I'm the father, basically.

25:10.042 --> 25:11.010
But thank you...

25:11.043 --> 25:12.178
Thank you.

25:12.211 --> 25:13.580
For everything.

25:16.616 --> 25:17.116
♪

25:29.962 --> 25:33.165
♪

25:33.199 --> 25:35.868
It seems sometimes,
maybe even all the time,

25:35.902 --> 25:39.071
like you can wander into
just anywhere in San Sebastián

25:39.105 --> 25:42.041
and find
fantastic things to eat.

25:42.074 --> 25:45.211
Casa Urola in the Old Town
does not outwardly look

25:45.244 --> 25:48.447
like a place
where you go to find this:

25:48.480 --> 25:51.050
seared mushrooms with egg yolk
and pine nuts.

25:51.083 --> 25:52.051
Potato sauce?

25:52.084 --> 25:53.620
Uh, yes, and that sauce.

25:53.653 --> 25:54.954
Beautiful.
Wow.

25:54.987 --> 25:56.088
Look at that.

25:56.122 --> 25:58.290
Grilled tuna
with "marmitako" sauce,

25:58.324 --> 26:00.526
a reference to a classic
fisherman's stew.

26:00.559 --> 26:03.562
Peas in a consommé
of ibérico ham.

26:03.596 --> 26:05.698
Oh, it's so pretty.

26:05.732 --> 26:07.199
The food is so good
in this town.

26:07.233 --> 26:08.735
I mean, it's really outrageous.
Yes.

26:08.768 --> 26:12.038
I mean, you walk by this
place, you don't expect this.

26:12.071 --> 26:14.373
Olatz González Abrisketa

26:14.406 --> 26:16.542
is a professor
of social anthropology

26:16.575 --> 26:18.210
and documentary filmmaker.

26:18.244 --> 26:19.746
Whoa, look at that.

26:19.779 --> 26:22.314
It's a squid
with a white bean cream.

26:22.348 --> 26:23.449
Wow.

26:23.482 --> 26:25.451
I know that this is
the end of squid season.

26:25.484 --> 26:26.552
Yeah.

26:26.585 --> 26:29.622
Everybody says...
I mean, everybody knows.

26:29.656 --> 26:31.924
The Basque obsession
or insistence

26:31.958 --> 26:34.393
on really,
really good ingredients.

26:34.426 --> 26:35.728
The fish has to be in season.

26:35.762 --> 26:38.064
It has to be incredibly fresh.

26:38.097 --> 26:40.566
The... it always has to be
the best of everything.

26:40.599 --> 26:44.737
I'm... The Basque are very
obsessive with qualities.

26:44.771 --> 26:46.305
For example, as you know,

26:46.338 --> 26:50.442
I did a thesis
in the Basque pelota.

26:53.112 --> 26:53.612
♪

26:57.784 --> 26:59.151
Pelota, if you didn't know,

26:59.185 --> 27:02.121
is the most popular sport
in Basque culture.

27:02.154 --> 27:04.323
Its origins go back
to the Middle Ages.

27:04.356 --> 27:07.159
The Basque are as obsessive
about this pastime

27:07.193 --> 27:09.095
as they are about food.

27:11.630 --> 27:12.130
♪

27:16.368 --> 27:18.838
Most of male conversation
in Basque country

27:18.871 --> 27:21.708
are about things and about
qualities of things.

27:21.741 --> 27:24.176
And they pass days and days

27:24.210 --> 27:27.446
in bouncing the balls
for the match,

27:27.479 --> 27:30.516
and they need to know
which one is the best

27:30.549 --> 27:32.785
for the match and how it behave.

27:35.822 --> 27:36.322
♪

27:43.062 --> 27:46.733
So the obsession and I think
a male obsession with quality

27:46.766 --> 27:50.236
is also something
which happen in sports

27:50.269 --> 27:52.471
just like with the food.

27:55.441 --> 27:58.978
♪

28:02.014 --> 28:02.514
♪

28:07.453 --> 28:09.088
Basque language and culture

28:09.121 --> 28:11.824
exists on both sides
of a border...

28:11.858 --> 28:15.728
Unsurprising,
as they predate both countries.

28:15.762 --> 28:20.099
This may be France,
but it's still pays Basque.

28:20.132 --> 28:22.501
Here we're in
the French Basque country.

28:22.534 --> 28:25.671
The Basque country
is divided by a frontier,

28:25.704 --> 28:28.340
but we're talking about
the same culture

28:28.374 --> 28:33.112
in the French Basque country
and the Spanish Basque country.

28:33.145 --> 28:36.916
Is there a difference between
the French and the Spanish side?

28:36.949 --> 28:40.186
Well, on the Spanish side,
it was the dictator, Franco.

28:40.219 --> 28:42.188
And there, it wasn't...

28:42.221 --> 28:43.956
It was forbidden
to speak in Basque.

28:43.990 --> 28:46.125
On the French side,
it's true that there was

28:46.158 --> 28:49.195
a little less pressure
about talking Basque,

28:49.228 --> 28:52.198
but because a lot of people
were coming from Paris,

28:52.231 --> 28:54.466
from the big towns
for retirement,

28:54.500 --> 28:56.702
we were losing
the Basque language.

28:56.735 --> 29:00.807
Do we drink Spanish wine?
Do we drink French wine?

29:00.840 --> 29:02.541
We drink French wine.
French wine.

29:02.574 --> 29:03.810
Oh, okay.

29:03.843 --> 29:06.412
♪

29:06.445 --> 29:07.980
We're in the town of Ahetze,

29:08.014 --> 29:10.482
at La Ferme Ostalapia.

29:10.516 --> 29:13.485
Miray Girt was born
in Spanish Basque country

29:13.519 --> 29:15.988
but raised in France.

29:16.022 --> 29:18.991
We've got a very good
quality of life here.

29:19.025 --> 29:21.828
The sea, the mountains.

29:21.861 --> 29:23.662
The Sun.

29:23.695 --> 29:25.231
- And the food.
- And the food.

29:26.532 --> 29:28.567
Things are different here.

29:28.600 --> 29:31.003
The relationship between
Basque and French cultures

29:31.037 --> 29:34.173
has always been more graceful
and less contentious,

29:34.206 --> 29:38.677
and you can see it and feel it
and taste it at the table.

29:38.710 --> 29:40.346
Ventrèche de thon,

29:40.379 --> 29:43.415
or tuna belly
with tomato carpaccio.

29:44.516 --> 29:46.685
Pigeon,
roasted and then flambéed,

29:46.718 --> 29:50.356
served with a terrine
or pâté of the same bird.

29:50.389 --> 29:51.924
On this side of the border,

29:51.958 --> 29:54.260
are the chefs as creative
or more traditional?

29:54.293 --> 29:57.529
They're more influenced
by the French...

29:57.563 --> 30:01.167
The French cuisine,
which is more complex.

30:01.200 --> 30:02.869
On the other side, we simplify.

30:02.902 --> 30:05.872
Here, we... it's a little bit
more complex.

30:08.908 --> 30:09.408
♪

30:13.913 --> 30:17.549
Why is the food so good

30:17.583 --> 30:19.718
Because we like eating.

30:19.751 --> 30:21.287
That's the main point.

30:21.320 --> 30:25.892
Why are we going to use things
which are in the freezer?

30:25.925 --> 30:28.560
You're going to try to do it
always fresh,

30:28.594 --> 30:31.530
very simple
but with very good things.

30:31.563 --> 30:35.067
I would say that would describe
the Basque cook.

30:35.101 --> 30:37.636
It's really simple but fresh.

30:40.672 --> 30:43.609
♪

30:52.218 --> 30:52.718
♪

31:52.411 --> 31:56.115
♪

32:20.506 --> 32:24.476
There is no better city
for food than this one.

32:24.510 --> 32:26.578
You know, look,
it's gonna be a problem,

32:26.612 --> 32:28.914
because you're gonna have,
like, millions and millions

32:28.947 --> 32:30.182
of tourists coming here to eat.

32:30.216 --> 32:31.617
- Yeah.
- You know? Every year, more.

32:31.650 --> 32:34.153
I think now
we are being discovered,

32:34.186 --> 32:36.588
not only by foreigners;
by Spanish people.

32:36.622 --> 32:37.823
- Yeah.
- This is what I heard.

32:37.856 --> 32:40.292
The only people from Spain
that came here

32:40.326 --> 32:42.661
all the time
were people from Barcelona,

32:42.694 --> 32:44.997
- Catalonians, of course.
- Catalonian.

32:45.031 --> 32:46.332
Absolutely.

32:46.365 --> 32:47.933
And some people from Madrid.
Some people.

32:47.966 --> 32:50.602
♪

32:50.636 --> 32:53.605
So-called "bro food"
in fact predates

32:53.639 --> 32:56.775
the advent of the Kobe slider
or donkey sauce

32:56.808 --> 32:59.345
and probably even the high five.

32:59.378 --> 33:01.180
Txokos are private

33:01.213 --> 33:04.016
and historically all male
gastronomical societies,

33:04.050 --> 33:07.286
though that gender rule
has changed with the times.

33:07.319 --> 33:11.457
It is still strictly Basque
and strictly members only.

33:11.490 --> 33:13.125
So was everybody born here?

33:13.159 --> 33:14.993
Are you from...
From San Sebastián?

33:15.027 --> 33:16.528
- San Sebastián.
- Most everybody.

33:16.562 --> 33:19.198
You're very lucky that
we are just here surrounded

33:19.231 --> 33:21.833
by the sea, the mountains,
the green mountains.

33:21.867 --> 33:24.036
So in just one hour distance,

33:24.070 --> 33:25.637
you have any kind
of fresh product.

33:25.671 --> 33:29.208
We consider food
as a part of our culture.

33:29.241 --> 33:32.711
I mean, the importance it has
in our daily life.

33:32.744 --> 33:33.712
I mean...
Yeah.

33:33.745 --> 33:35.314
This is the best example
right here.

33:35.347 --> 33:37.001
There's one thing
that my dad always said.

33:37.015 --> 33:39.218
We may not have money
to go on holidays

33:39.251 --> 33:42.054
or to buy a new car
or even to buy new shoes,

33:42.088 --> 33:43.322
but food?

33:43.355 --> 33:44.923
So important.
So important.

33:44.956 --> 33:47.159
♪

33:47.193 --> 33:49.895
Who cooks rotates
between members.

33:49.928 --> 33:51.863
Tonight it's Pablo.

33:51.897 --> 33:55.234
The menu: diced raw tuna,

33:55.267 --> 33:57.736
grilled prawns with green sauce.

33:57.769 --> 34:01.340
You notice that we don't like
herbs or spices at all.

34:01.373 --> 34:02.841
Nothing. Nothing.
We don't.

34:02.874 --> 34:06.078
So the most we use,
parsley and garlic.

34:06.112 --> 34:08.013
Of course garlic, onion,
all the way.

34:08.045 --> 34:10.081
Because, yeah,
people have the idea

34:10.116 --> 34:12.684
if you add many spices and herbs

34:12.717 --> 34:14.853
to something
that you're cooking here,

34:14.886 --> 34:17.356
you might be suspicious
about maybe the...

34:17.389 --> 34:18.382
It's not so fresh.
Not fresh.

34:18.389 --> 34:19.757
- Fresh.
- Not fresh. Yeah.

34:19.791 --> 34:23.027
You want to take this food
and put in another country,

34:23.061 --> 34:25.864
maybe Moscow, maybe New York.

34:25.897 --> 34:27.966
It's impossible to cook
in this way.

34:27.998 --> 34:30.369
And people don't understand.

34:33.405 --> 34:35.806
♪

34:39.610 --> 34:40.110
♪

34:45.417 --> 34:48.954
Now, someone I was talking to
yesterday had a theory.

34:48.987 --> 34:53.458
She said the men talk about
the difference between things.

34:53.492 --> 34:55.827
The difference between this
bicycle and that bicycle.

34:55.860 --> 34:59.131
The difference between this
bicyclist and that bicyclist.

34:59.165 --> 35:03.602
And that this is an innate part
of the Basque culture.

35:03.635 --> 35:05.437
I don't think
it's exclusively from here.

35:05.471 --> 35:08.974
I think this is something
that from Franco years.

35:09.007 --> 35:10.742
Where's Franco buried,
by the way?

35:10.776 --> 35:12.010
Oh, Madrid.

35:12.043 --> 35:13.179
Valle de los Caídos.

35:13.212 --> 35:14.646
Valle de los Caídos.

35:14.680 --> 35:16.541
Big gravestone or they just
sort of roll him into a ditch?

35:16.548 --> 35:19.251
It's a huge place.

35:19.285 --> 35:22.020
If you were... I'm just...
I'm not suggesting you do this.

35:22.053 --> 35:24.089
But if you were to visit
Franco's grave,

35:24.122 --> 35:26.658
unzip, and take a piss on it,

35:26.692 --> 35:28.927
would you be arrested?
Yep.

35:28.960 --> 35:30.522
No, you will be in the news
all over the world.

35:30.529 --> 35:32.964
Would that make you popular
or unpopular?

35:32.998 --> 35:33.965
Uh, popular.

35:33.999 --> 35:35.434
Popular, yeah.

35:38.337 --> 35:38.837
♪

35:44.410 --> 35:47.346
For the main,
fried hake cooked with txakoli

35:47.379 --> 35:48.480
and steamed clams.

35:51.517 --> 35:52.017
♪

36:02.027 --> 36:05.063
So what's the best thing
about this city for you?

36:05.096 --> 36:06.998
I mean, you've lived here
your whole lives.

36:07.032 --> 36:09.568
Having so many things so near.

36:09.601 --> 36:11.337
I mean, I have France near.

36:11.370 --> 36:13.004
I have all the coasts near.

36:13.038 --> 36:14.473
I have the mountains near.

36:14.506 --> 36:16.875
I have very,
very good gastronomy.

36:16.908 --> 36:18.510
It's the way of life.

36:18.544 --> 36:20.212
And it's a way of life.

36:20.246 --> 36:22.013
You are able to
keep the very same

36:22.047 --> 36:24.316
group of friends
till you are old.

36:24.350 --> 36:26.652
You can see it here.
Because-Yes, that table.

36:26.685 --> 36:28.654
And they're in 40s.

36:28.687 --> 36:31.823
And I'm sure
they know each other from

36:31.857 --> 36:35.026
they are 10 or 5 years old.

36:35.060 --> 36:37.829
And they keep on coming here
every week

36:37.863 --> 36:39.998
and have dinner here every week.

36:43.034 --> 36:43.534
♪

36:55.080 --> 36:57.115
Here?

37:04.055 --> 37:04.555
♪

37:46.598 --> 37:48.900
This place,
deep in the Atxondo Valley

37:48.934 --> 37:51.136
about an hour
outside of San Sebastián

37:51.169 --> 37:52.571
is Etxebarri,

37:52.604 --> 37:55.140
one of the greatest,
most iconoclastic,

37:55.173 --> 37:58.644
and most loved by chefs
restaurants in the world.

37:58.677 --> 38:02.314
It is in every way,
extraordinary.

38:02.348 --> 38:03.482
Sometimes with chefs,

38:03.515 --> 38:05.417
we sit around
and we play this game.

38:05.451 --> 38:08.420
If you had to die at one
restaurant, you know,

38:08.454 --> 38:10.589
what would your last meal...
What restaurant

38:10.622 --> 38:12.157
would you like
your last meal at?

38:12.190 --> 38:13.825
And they were coming up
with restaurants,

38:13.859 --> 38:15.827
and I said, "Well,
what about Etxe..."

38:15.861 --> 38:17.262
It's Etxebarri?
Etxebarri.

38:17.295 --> 38:19.097
And they all
changed their answer.

38:19.130 --> 38:20.191
They said, "Oh, no, no,
you're right."

38:20.198 --> 38:21.867
That place."

38:21.900 --> 38:24.035
- Yeah.
- It's... It's so perfect.

38:24.069 --> 38:27.939
My lunch companion is my old
friend Virginia Irizar.

38:27.973 --> 38:29.174
With her father,

38:29.207 --> 38:31.977
she runs the
Escuela de Cocina Luis Irizar,

38:32.010 --> 38:35.781
her father being Luis Irizar,
of the original group of 12

38:35.814 --> 38:37.516
and the man
who first showed me...

38:37.549 --> 38:40.686
Well,
everything in San Sebastián.

38:40.719 --> 38:43.455
Your dad's first job out here
was at the Maria Cristina

38:43.489 --> 38:44.623
Is that true?

38:44.656 --> 38:45.624
He started there?

38:45.657 --> 38:46.692
16 years old.

38:46.725 --> 38:48.727
His first duty was to

38:48.760 --> 38:53.064
keep the white wine ice cold
for the chef.

38:53.098 --> 38:54.132
Well...

38:54.165 --> 38:55.534
Otherwise, they were in trouble.

38:55.567 --> 38:56.668
That's understandable.

38:56.702 --> 38:58.570
So what did they do
that was different?

38:58.604 --> 39:03.642
They did try to modernize
Basque traditional food,

39:03.675 --> 39:07.646
make it less heavy, less greasy,
that sort of thing.

39:07.679 --> 39:10.816
♪

39:10.849 --> 39:13.419
And this man,
Victor Arguinzoniz,

39:13.452 --> 39:14.920
is a legend.

39:14.953 --> 39:18.657
He is a master of
what looks austere and simple

39:18.690 --> 39:21.326
but is in fact
in an almost Japanese way

39:21.359 --> 39:23.695
fetishistically perfectionist

39:23.729 --> 39:25.997
in his treatment
of local ingredients.

39:26.031 --> 39:28.834
Victor cooks everything himself,

39:28.867 --> 39:33.004
from his own charcoal
made from wood he cuts himself.

39:33.038 --> 39:35.340
Chorizo, which he makes
from Iberian pork loin

39:35.373 --> 39:38.343
served over a tiny little grill
still smoking

39:38.376 --> 39:41.246
and infusing it
with scent and flavor.

39:42.714 --> 39:44.015
Mmm!

39:44.049 --> 39:45.016
Oh, so good.

39:45.050 --> 39:47.385
Grilled razor clams.

39:47.419 --> 39:49.354
So good, so simple.

39:49.387 --> 39:50.689
Beluga caviar,

39:50.722 --> 39:53.459
however improbably it sounds,
grilled

39:53.492 --> 39:55.761
and heaped over almond paste.

39:55.794 --> 39:56.928
Excuse me.

39:56.962 --> 39:58.122
I'm gonna have to
take a picture of this.

39:58.129 --> 39:59.390
I'm gonna make
other people feel bad

39:59.397 --> 40:00.532
about what they're eating.

40:00.566 --> 40:01.700
Grilled gambas:

40:01.733 --> 40:04.402
perfectly,
perfectly cooked prawns.

40:04.436 --> 40:06.204
- It's huge!
- Yeah.

40:06.237 --> 40:08.206
- This is...
- Wow.

40:09.508 --> 40:11.309
Line caught squid

40:11.342 --> 40:14.045
grilled and served
in its own ink.

40:14.079 --> 40:15.881
Beautiful.

40:15.914 --> 40:17.315
It's very nice.

40:18.784 --> 40:20.218
And the most delicious:

40:20.251 --> 40:22.888
king hell Galician beef chop,

40:22.921 --> 40:26.892
grilled, perfectly rested,
and ready.

40:26.925 --> 40:29.160
Ooh!
Look at that.

40:29.194 --> 40:31.396
Why are the ingredients so good?

40:31.429 --> 40:35.734
I mean, the basic ingredients
are always super high-quality...

40:35.767 --> 40:37.268
- Mm-hmm.
- Everywhere.

40:37.302 --> 40:38.837
Where does this come from?

40:38.870 --> 40:42.007
I think it's just that we
wouldn't have it any other way.

40:42.040 --> 40:43.909
I mean...
It's as simple as that.

